{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UrCB3jVmEEThL2mPxkw8cE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Looking at the logs, the controller started with the ConfigMap (`resourceVersion: \"52587\"` - which matches what I see in the ConfigMap). The TOML file has the correct sampler (AlwaysOn) and service name, but `host = \"\"`. \n\nThis is a bug or limitation in ingress-nginx v1.14.1. The `otel-otlp-collector-host` key might not be properly used to populate the TOML. Looking at the ingress-nginx source code:\n\nIn the ingress-nginx source code (https://github.com/kubernetes/ingress-nginx), the template for opentelemetry.toml is:\nThe template uses a placeholder for the host that should be populated from the config parsing, which maps `otel-otlp-collector-host` to the correct field. So the key mapping looks right, but somehow the host value isn't making it through to the rendered TOML even though other fields like the sampler and service name are being set correctly.\n\nI'm wondering if newer versions of ingress-nginx (v1.10+) might be using the `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` environment variable instead of the TOML configuration for the collector host, which would explain why the TOML comment mentions that as an alternative approach. is empty, maybe the issue is that the template isn't properly substituting the host value from the annotation. Let me try a different approach - I could set the `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` environment variable directly on the nginx controller container, or create a custom ConfigMap with the correct TOML configuration and reference it via the `opentelemetry-config` annotation instead of relying on the template substitution. the TOML file gets regenerated from the controller's configuration, so template substitution should handle it. Let me check the ingress-nginx source code to see what key name is used for the collector host in v1.14.1 - it might be different from what I'm expecting, and that could explain why the host isn't being set properly. Looking at the TOML configuration, I see the comment mentions that `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` can be used as an alternative when the host is empty. Let me set that environment variable in the deployment instead of trying to modify the config file. The nginx-otel module itself reads `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT`, and since nginx runs as a child process of the controller, environment variables set on the pod should be inherited. But I should verify whether the ConfigMap key `otel-otlp-collector-host` is being parsed correctly in the first place—the ingress-nginx source uses lowercase dash-separated keys that map to camelCase properties, so I need to check if that's the actual issue before adding the env var.\n\nActually, the simplest approach is to just patch the deployment with `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` directly, since that's explicitly supported. Alternatively, I could mount a ConfigMap as a volume with the proper TOML content and update the opentelemetry-config key, but that requires patching both the deployment and the ConfigMap. Let me start with the env var approach first.\n\nI need to figure out the correct format for the endpoint — the TOML uses `host:port` for gRPC, so I should try `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT=otel-collector.otel.svc:4317`. But I'm realizing I need to verify whether the nginx_otel module actually reads environment variables or if it only uses the TOML file.\n\nThe most reliable approach is to create a ConfigMap with the correct TOML configuration and mount it directly into the ingress-nginx controller deployment, then update the ingress-nginx Config to point to that file path.\n\nBut I should double-check the exact ConfigMap key name that ingress-nginx expects—it might be `opentelemetry-otlp-collector-host` rather than `otel-otlp-collector-host`. Let me look at the ingress-nginx v1.14.1 source to find the right key pattern.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":nul